<header>
<h1>Public Health Surveillance</h1>
<h2 class='subtitle'>Foundations, Processes &amp; Global Perspectives</h2>
</header>

<section id='definition'>
<h2>Definition</h2>
<p>Public health surveillance is the <strong>continuous, systematic</strong> collection, analysis and interpretation of health‑related data needed for the planning, implementation and evaluation of public‑health practice, closely integrated with the timely dissemination of these data to those who need to know and linked to public‑health action. <span class='cite'>(WHO 2024; CDC 2024)</span></p>
</section>

<section id='strategic-objectives'>
<h2>Strategic Objectives</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Early detection</strong> of unusual public‑health events and emerging threats.</li>
<li><strong>Monitoring trends</strong> in disease incidence, prevalence and determinants.</li>
<li><strong>Guiding interventions</strong> and resource allocation for prevention and control.</li>
<li><strong>Evaluating impact</strong> of policies and programmes.</li>
<li><strong>Supporting research</strong> and innovation for healthier populations.</li>
<li><strong>Enabling global health security</strong> through data sharing and collaboration.</li>
</ol>
</section>

